27	Amazon Machine Learning: Super Simple Supervised Learning	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1536412809910_a-2729794_640.png	Amazon Machine Learning (AML) is a managed service that makes it easy to to build machine learning models and expose them for predictions. AML is for you if you want to explore machine learning technology without math or complicated software installs. AML is also for you if you need predictions on structured data at medium scale (up to 100GB of input data).\n\nIn this talk, we'll cover:\n\n* a brief overview of machine learning terms\n* what problems this tech is appropriate for\n* where to put your data, and in what format it can be\n* how you can transform that data before the model processes it\n* how to create a model, and limits on that model\n* how to access that model to make real time predictions (in under 100ms)\n* how to access that model asynchronously to process large amounts of data (up to 1 TB of )\n* alternatives if AML doesn't fit your needs\n\nThere will be a demonstration of building a model against sample data as well.\n\nI've created the O'Reilly video course on this technology. I'm a former AWS course instructor and current engineering manager.	698	2018-09-08 13:21:30.636419+00	t	devops
50	Always Be Interviewing -- Keys to a Happy Career and Life	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1536857868074_5a0c1d4252d9263c7a157171dcb9db33.jpg	# Brief Summary\n\nYou could be in a great company.  You could be in a bad one.  It doesn't matter.\n\nThe fact is, you don't know what's going to happen six months from now.  And you shouldn't be behind the 8-ball if the something out of your control occurs that results in your unemployment.\n\n# Who Am I\n\nPaul has built cross-functional teams large and small in New York, Colorado, and California in multiple industries including software engineering, healthcare, childcare, and cannabis.  And he's always advocated this mantra to all employees.\n\nHe is currently a happy software engineer at Skookum, an incredible software design and delivery consulting firm here in Denver.\n\n# Takeaways\n\n* When to start the interview process\n* Why you should interview, even if you're super happy where you are\n* Why frustrations don't always mean you should leave\n* Why employers should encourage this, and hiring managers should also be out interviewing\n* How to weigh your opportunities\n* Opportunities for a happier life if you employ this methodology\n\n# Overview\n\nThe interviewing process takes months, and you should court a lot of prospects during that time.  Just like dating, you shouldn't take the first opportunity that is presented just because its there and you need it, you should take the BEST opportunity.  You spend over 2000 hours every year at work, and you should be happy there.  If you ignore this search only to start when you no longer have a paycheck, you're very likely to miss the best opportunity.  \n\nYou may be in a great place, but little things are bothering you.  Interviewing elsewhere also gives you perspective to help you realize the strengths of your organization, or discover solutions you can take back to fix problems other companies have solved.\n\nYou may think you've been doing great work but don't get compensated enough.  Go find out what you're worth.  If everyone followed this idea, it would actually raise the entire market rate for developers.\n\nFor the employers out there, this idea shouldn't be something to be afraid of, and if you're confident in your company, it should be encouraged.  The best way to bring in a strong team is to present your company strongly in the interview, and be confident with your strengths and weaknesses.  Employers should also be interviewing elsewhere, to understand your competition in talent acquisition and learn how you can put your company's best foot forward.\n\nWe'll review this and a whole lot more about setting yourself up for success and happiness in your career and your life.	721	2018-09-13 16:58:02.248662+00	t	careers
45	Re-imagine JavaScript & React development	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1536697898760_Screen%20Shot%202018-09-11%20at%205.31.20%20PM.png	Ok, I know the title is a bit pretentious but I needed the mandatory "Re" in all reasonml talks. Reason is a -not so- new language that's making JavaScript development easier and safer by making the right concessions.\n\n# What this talk is not about\nThis is not a talk about FP, one can be tempted to talk about all the features the language has, why it's great, and why everybody else is wrong about programming, but I don't have time for that nor the people in need of delivering a feature for yesterday.\n\n# What this talk is all about\nThis talk is about Reason in your everyday workflow, how to create React components, how to take advantage of the type system and how to interact with all the code you already have and don't want to write again.\n\nMy goal is to provide you with enough hype to get started and enough tools to add Reason to your codebase similarly to how you add a new babel plugin.\n\n# Questions & answers\n* Isn't an ambitious goal? Yes, definitely. But it's also doable in 30 minutes; I just need to talk very fast\n* Am I a great Reason developer? Absolutely no. I think that's why the talk could work; I'll cut corners and avoid saying monad, I'm interested in the language as a tool for doing my day job easier\n* Am I as histrionic as I sound in this CFP? Only on stage	212	2018-09-11 20:23:17.250627+00	t	development
30	So You Want to Build Your Own Programming Language	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1536441860372_animal-animal-photography-cattle-51952.jpg	Maybe you've taken an alternative to JavaScript like Elm, PureScript, for ReasonML for a spin. I don't know—maybe, you miss CoffeeScript. In this talk, we'll take a tour of how you can build your very own language. Building languages in a metric ton of fun and will make you better at this whole software racket. We'll talk about compiling to JavaScript because time is short, but these concepts apply to compiled languages as well.	151	2018-09-08 21:34:10.300025+00	t	development
65	Introverts and Extroverts: How You Can Help Your Teammates Shine	lightning	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1537218485462_introvertextrovert.png	Whether you consider yourself an introvert or an extrovert, chances are you work within a team of people that view and experience the world differently than you. \n\nIn this talk, we'll celebrate the qualities that can make an introvert or an extrovert a great teammate and how you can help them flourish.	718	2018-09-17 21:10:18.482354+00	t	product
66	All Roads Lead to root: Bootcampers, Self-Taughters, and Traditional University Graduates Discuss Tech Education	panel	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1537219037734_coding-class-for-our-employees.jpg	A panel of bootcampers, self-taught engineers, and traditional university grads discuss how they they broke into the industry and how their educational background led them to the jobs they have now.	718	2018-09-17 21:17:40.386564+00	t	product
71	You Can Be A Unicorn! Code Concepts For Designers	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1537390070239_vp0U8zo.gif	The design/dev unicorns exist. But they typically aren’t born, they are made. Join a designer and a coder and together we will journey through an enchanted forest of core programming concepts for designers. You’ll learn how to level up technical comprehension and why that matters so much to teams on their quests to collaborate better on ideas and implementation. By the end of this conversation, you’ll be able to slay the dragons of miscommunication, implementation misalignment, or feeling just plain powerless.	64	2018-09-19 20:47:57.896601+00	t	product
8	Demystifying Accessibility	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1536105444819_AdobeStock_168422442.jpeg	As organizations build accessible applications the need for developers who understand how accessibility impacts users is rising. In this talk we will confront misconceptions about what accessibility is and isn’t, while taking an interactive look at how to build inclusive experiences.\n\n**During this talk we will:**\n\n- Learn about diverse abilities and user needs\n- Explore types of assistive technology\n- Code snippets for specific situations and use cases	672	2018-09-05 00:05:20.439757+00	t	product
18	From Concept to Production: How to Launch Your Passion Project. (Tips from a Product Manager turned Developer)	talk	https://develop-denver-user-images.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/1538672292353_full_stack_wide-7.jpg	You're like Jack Black in [Orange County](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KcRJ_HCWWTw&t=0m24s), you've got all these ideas! But most of the time, they stay that way: just ideas. \n\nIn this talk, we'll go past the idea stage. We'll talk about:\n * How to think big picture (Oh the places your app can go!)\n * How to slash that big picture down to an MVP\n * How to pick the right technologies\n * How to make milestones to track your progress\n * How to manage the emotional rollercoaster of passion projects\n * How to push through plateaus and dry spells\n * Most importantly: How to get your passion project launched!\n \nMy good friend and I spent 8 months taking our whiteboard idea and turning it into a live app on the AppStore. I'd like to share some of what we learned with you.\n \n Let's get excited together, and let's get your idea into production!	143	2018-09-07 01:34:24.060138+00	t	product
